{"text": "Published: Technical analysis can help point the way in uncertain times By The stock market is complex. The number of inputs is staggering. Setting aside the complexity, the simplest thing investors can do to gain valuable insight is to look at patterns. To explore what might be next for stocks, let\u2019s look at a chart.   Please click to see an annotated chart of S&P 500 futures Similar conclusions can be drawn from popular ETFs such as S&P 500 ETF Nasdaq 100 ETF and small-cap ETF It is more instructive to use a futures chart because futures trade overnight and there is a very important point on the chart that is visible only on the futures chart. Please note the following from the chart: \u2022 In recent history, most of the very shallow dips formed a V pattern. In a V pattern, the dip is bought and the market recovers. When the market dipped this time, many were expecting a V bottom. The chart shows that a V bottom did not occur. This was addressed in the early stages of the stock market dip, when many gurus were predicting a V bottom. From the Morning Capsule made available to subscribers of The Arora Report: \u201cIf the stock market continues to go up from here, it would have formed a V bottom yesterday. Historically, V bottoms are less common than the retest. If a retest were to occur, the market would fall back to yesterday\u2019s lows. The momo [momentum] crowd likely has stops under yesterday\u2019s lows. A typical scenario would be hunt-and-destroy algorithms to become active, take out stops of the momo crowd and then for the market to rebound. If a retest occurs and it fails, then the probability of something more than a garden-variety correction will rise.\u201d This observation has now proven spot on. A V bottom did not occur this time. \u2022 The chart shows that a retest of the prior low marked with a horizontal white line is in progress. \u2022 The chart shows two scenarios from here on that will result in a bullish W pattern. These are shown with green dotted lines on the chart. \u2022 The chart also shows two scenarios if the retest fails. This will be a bearish break. These scenarios are shown with dotted red lines on the chart.        It is high time to remind investors of Arora\u2019s Second Law Of Investing: \u201cNo one knows with certainty what is going to happen next.\u201d The best way to handle uncertainty is to think in terms of probabilities. The probability of a bullish W pattern forming is significantly higher than a bearish break.   In addition to the simple chart, those interested in a comprehensive approach may look at The Arora Report timing model with inputs in 10 categories. The model is adaptive, i.e., it changes automatically with market conditions. To see the 10 inputs, please click .   Many investors are overly concentrated in technology. Some investors mistakenly think that just because they own several ETFs and mutual funds, they are diversified. Take a look at the holdings of your ETFs and mutual funds. You will find over-concentration in Apple Microsoft Facebook Amazon and Google  If there is a bearish break, those stocks have the highest risk. If you are overly concentrated, consider trimming the positions on bounces in the market. To be helpful, the following articles are provided to you for the information, understanding and action items for current market conditions. \u2022 \u2022 \u2022 \u2022 \u2022     Nigam Arora is an engineer, nuclear physicist, author, and entrepreneur and the founder of two Inc. 500 fastest growing companies. He is also the developer of the ZYX Change Method to profit from change by investing. The premise is that most money is made by predicting change before the crowd. Arora is the chief investment officer at The Arora Report and the editor of four newsletters that track the ZYX Change Method. Nigam can be reached at Nigam@TheAroraReport.com Nigam Arora is an engineer, nuclear physicist, author, and entrepreneur and the founder of two Inc. 500 fastest growing companies. He is also the developer of the ZYX Change Method to profit from change by investing. The premise is that most money is made by predicting change before the crowd. Arora is the chief investment officer at The Arora Report and the editor of four newsletters that track the ZYX Change Method. Nigam can be reached at Nigam@TheAroraReport.com Join the conversation Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and .", "link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/whats-next-for-stocks-a-bullish-pattern-or-a-bearish-break-2018-02-09", "source": "MarketWatch", "author": "Nigam Arora", "tick": "AAPL", "headline": "Stock market patterns suggest bullishness will triumph over bearishness - MarketWatch"}
{"text": "Asia continuing to increase in importance for Apple. Reports of lukewarm response to iPhone X in China proved to be false. Whole Apple product range showing strength in Asia. Asian macro economic factors suggest the continent will become increasingly vital for Apple. Of all the comments about Q1 2018 results for Apple (NASDAQ: ) many analysts have not emphasized how strongly Apple is performing in Asia. My predicted Apple's results would show stronger growth in Asia than anticipated. So it turned out. This shows how Asia will become increasingly important to the company and be the single strongest growth driver in coming years. An analysis of the illustrate the growth from Asia. The unaudited data summary shows this in relation to revenue as below: The net sales by reportable segment is as follows: The figures are striking. In terms of revenue year-on-year: Americas + 10% Europe +14% Greater China +11% Japan + 26% Rest of Asia Pacific + 17% In terms of revenue sequential change: Americas + 52% Europe + 62% Greater China +83% Japan + 88% Rest of Asia Pacific +144% The figures show that Asia is the fastest-growing sector in terms of growth in the medium term. In the short term they are very much the fastest-growing sector in terms of growth. Much of this huge accelerating growth short term is caused by the impact of the iPhone X. However it is backed up by the full product portfolio. In terms of net sales, China now represents 20.3%. Japan represents 8.2%. Rest of Asia Pacific represents 7.8%. That gives Asia 36.3% of total net sales for the company. On the , executives placed more emphasis on Asia than they had in the past with certain key comments. The iPhone X lead the charge in the region, but it was not just this model. This was despite negative calls by some analysts. As CEO Tim Cook stated: \"In urban China ...the top five smartphones last quarter were all iPhones...In Japan six of the seven were iPhones.\" As for the iPad, rumors of its death have been somewhat exaggerated. As Tim Cook said: \"In China, new and switching users made up over 70% of all iPad sales.\" So the product has a new lease of life there. Elsewhere, iPad enjoyed double-digit growth in India, Japan, Australia and Korea. As for the Mac, Cook contrasted: \"Worldwide 60% of our Mac sales were to first-time buyers and switchers and in China that number was almost 90%....We grew market share for iPhone in the quarter but we also grew share in iPad and Mac during the quarter and wearables were extremely strong.\" He pointed out also that although China numbers showed an 11% increase for Greater China, if one took this on an average weekly revenue basis, the numbers were up 19%. Double-digit revenue growth for a second quarter in a row hardly ties in with the picture some had tried to paint of a decline in China. It is true that forecasts indicate a difficult year for mobile phone volumes in general in China in 2018. These may or may not turn out to be accurate. However there is no reason to suppose Apple won't increase its market share. Other new product developments hold out great promise for Apple in Asia. In a continent where cashless payment is increasingly king, Apple Pay continues to move ahead. As Cook exampled: \"Today you can use Apple Pay to take a subway in Guangzhou.\" This is despite the very well-entrenched cashless payments already on tap in the country. In Singapore Apple Pay also is to the MRT and bus systems there, as just one example. The company also is cooperating with local rivals. It just recently that it will now accept \" \" the system from Alibaba (NYSE: ) in its stores in China. Previously it had accepted \"Alipay\" on its digital stores. In a way the company had little option but to cooperate with the world's largest mobile as an online payments platform. Augmented reality is very big in China as well, and this fits well with Cook's enthusiasm for it. As he stated: \"I am a huge, huge believer in AR. We put a lot of energy on AR moving very fast.\" Cook is wise to emphasize this. Chinese heavyweight companies Alibaba, Baidu (NASDAQ: ) and Tencent ( ) all have substantial mobile AR initiatives under way. These are not just in the world of gaming (inspired by Pokemon \"Go\") but involve tourism, education, healthcare and entertainment. The situation with home automation is similar in China and elsewhere in Asia. Governments in the region worry about increased labour costs and ponder how to enable \"smart cities.\" The Apple \"Home Pod\" is likely to be greeted positively in the region. As last year detailed, the new products from Apple seem to be perfectly geared to appeal to Asian consumers. Brand loyalty and mobile lifestyles are paramount. Apple's well-known halo effect where the iPhone leads into the whole Apple infrastructure is taking off around the region. This just replicates what was seen in North America, Europe and Japan in the past. Tim Cook has shown that he is in China for the long term. He also has shown that he's willing to cooperate with the Chinese government and make compromises where necessary. Apple's in the country was set up at Guizhou, at a cost of US $1billion. A at Ulanqab in Mongolia is now set to open in 2020. The iPhone will continue to lead the charge. Those observers who over the years state that iPhones will be too expensive for the Chinese market have been proved wrong time and again. Last year as , the iPhone 7 Plus was the second best selling model in the country, only just below the much cheaper Oppo R95. The iPhone 7 was the fifth best seller. Worldwide Appl its biggest competitor Samsung (OTCMKTS: ) in 2017. Its Korean rival has been hit by a lack of excitement in its new models. Similarly Chinese manufacturers have been waxing and waning. Huawei, Oppo, Vivo and One Plus have all seen sales decline after an initial surge in their new low-cost models. Each one was previously cited by some analysts as sounding a potential death-knell for the iPhone in the country. According to from Kantar, the iPhone was the top-selling model in China in the last quarter of 2017. came out with a figure of 7 million sold in China in the last quarter of 2017 out of 29 million sold worldwide. These are just the latest datapoints illustrating the way in which expensive iPhones are able to sell well in China. The iOS market share in China rose 10.1%. The also seems to be finally turning in Apple's favor in China. The renminbi is at a three-year low against the US dollar. The past strength of the US dollar has enabled Apple to invest more cheaply in the country. Now a weaker US dollar improves Apple's US dollar profitability in its ever more important overseas markets. The U.S. government policy on the dollar is incoherent but it seems likely Trump himself wants a cheap dollar policy which will benefit Apple's profit figures. Exact sales figures for the Apple Watch are not broken down by the company. It is generally considered though that sales are very strong in China, as I . China already is the t for watch sales. The new Watch 3 has had some due to lack of LTE connectivity of the new eSIM chip, but this is only a short-term problem. Elsewhere in Asia luxury watches are big business. For instance Singapore, a very small country, is nevertheless the world's tenth largest watch market. Local telecoms company Singtel is now for the new Watch 3. Australia, Hong Kong and Japan are up and running. Others will follow suit within the next few months. On the back of this Apple's health applications such as \"Health Kit\" and \"Research Kit\" and the open-source \"Care Kit\" should resonate strongly in the region. They tie in with various Chinese Government initiatives in this regard. The wearables market is set to boom in Asia and especially in China, as I in June last year. The growing population of Asia, its youth dynamic beloved of economists and the region's GDP growth means Asia will only become more important in the short term, in the medium term, and in the long term. There are 4.3 billion people in Asia. This represents 60% of the world's population. Currently it is only 34% of the world's GDP. Its percentage share though is growing rapidly. The graphic below illustrates world economic GDP activity as calculated by the World Bank. Asia's 34% of world GDP contrasts with 28% for North America and 21% for Europe. Its lead in share of world economic GDP will only increase as its economies and demographics are favourable. This shows up clearly in IMF forecasts. GDP growth figures going forward for all countries in Asia can be viewed in the Apple's recent increasing reliance on Asia is only set to increase on the basis of the above data. Many of the benefits in China apply elsewhere in Asia. Amongst these is Apple's build-up of stores in the region. They have been somewhat late to do this, as I have written about Asia represents 36.3% of total net sales for the company but has only 11% of worldwide stores. Now they seem finally to be making up for lost time. The is for a huge \"global flagship store\" in Melbourne. This will be only the fifth such store worldwide. There are currently 22 stores in China where iOS market share grew 1.2% in the final quarter of the year. New stores have recently opened in Singapore (said to be the second busiest in the world), Bangkok and Seoul. Japan meanwhile continues to be the standout market for Apple in Asia, and perhaps worldwide. It was no surprise that the iPhone X jumped to being the in the country with an 18.2% market share. The best selling phone in the country was the iPhone 8. Last year over half of all mobile phones sold in the country were from Apple. 46% of tablets sold in the country are iPads. An of mine detailed the great depth of the Apple brand in the country where iOS market share is over 50%. Apple Pay has been flourishing there on the transit systems, despite the already advanced state of contactless payment in Japan. It is integrated with the Osaifu Keitai mobile wallet system which you see everywhere in the country. The company is driving its gaming revenue in Japan in conjunction with Nintendo ( OTCMKTS: ). This is very likely to be another strong growth stream for apple in the country. Apple products particularly appeal to the Japanese because of their minimalism and design features. However the market in general is an indication of what Apple could achieve elsewhere in Asia. Brand loyalty is a major driver to sales all around Asia. This is especially true in the IT space. The three most in the Asia Pacific region are Apple, Samsung and Sony (NYSE: ). India will be a huge driver of future growth in Asia for Apple. I will be covering that big topic in a separate article. India has the potential to be another China story for the company and increase further the vital importance of the region for Asia. Asia is what makes Apple still very much a potential growth company. Apple's valuation metrics though are very low and certainly not those of a growth company. For instance if you compare Apple to the S&P US BMI Information Technology sector: PE 16.42 (S&P 31.2). Price to Forecasted Earnings 13.84 (S&P 21.75). Price/Sales 3.38 (S&P 4.21). Price / Tangible Book 6.13 (S&P 6.03) Price / Cash Flow 14.02 (S&P 18.77). The latest stock market turmoil only adds to the attractive investment potential in the long run. Apple's growth in Asia is faster than in any other region. The region itself is a faster growing region than any other in the world. Apple's product mix reflect what Asian consumers want. Its increased retail roll-out in the region is important for consumer branding and service. In my opinion the growing importance of Asia to Apple has been underestimated in many quarters and will only grow.   I wrote this article myself, and it expresses my own opinions. I am not receiving compensation for it (other than from Seeking Alpha). I have no business relationship with any company whose stock is mentioned in this article. The chat platform is currently undergoing maintenance. To see the chat, try to refresh in about 5-10 minutes. Chat is not supported in your browser version. Please upgrade your browser or use a different browser, such as Google Chrome. You do not have permissions for this room.", "link": "https://seekingalpha.com/article/4145223-apple-results-confirm-importance-asia?source=marketwatch", "source": "MarketWatch", "author": "Nick Cox", "tick": "AAPL", "headline": "Apple Results Confirm Importance Of Asia - Apple Inc. (NASDAQ:AAPL) | Seeking Alpha"}
{"text": "Menu Source: Shutterstock A stock market correction has a habit of revealing bargains, the way a falling tide may reveal sunken treasures in the mud. (NASDAQ: ) is looking like one of those bargains. At its Feb. 9 opening price of $155.50, AAPL stock is selling for less than 16 times earnings, and while , you should still get that 63 cents per share dividend (or more) this spring, yielding 1.62%. Despite what was termed a disappointing quarter, Apple is still growing. Its sales of $88.2 billion in the fourth quarter were up 12% from the $78.3 billion of the same quarter the year before. The percentage of sales that went to the net income line, 23%, was even higher than a year earlier. Then there is all that cash \u2014 $163 billion going into stock Even after that, the company will still have the capability of writing a check to pay off its $122 billion in debt, if that were needed. Apple covers its dividend with income by nearly four times over, meaning there is plenty of room for another permanent hike. The cash being repatriated comes to a whopping $32 per share. Bret Kenwell calls Apple to buy on the current pullback. (NYSE: ) . The February losses dropped it another 2.75%. Since the start of February, Apple is down 7.3%, while the is down 8.5%. Apple was last selling at these prices in late October. That\u2019s not to say Apple, and the market, can\u2019t go lower. At the end of trading Feb. 8, the average stock was trading at a multiple of 24.1. That is high by historical standards. With interest rates higher, rising dividends like those at Apple become less interesting, and growth no longer draws the premium it once did. The question now becomes, what can Apple do from here? Apple\u2019s fourth quarter report included . This makes things like the iCloud and Apple Music its second-largest business, behind only the iPhone. It is also Apple\u2019s fastest-growing business, rising 34% year over year. It\u2019s services that make the launch of , the company\u2019s answer to Alexa from (NASDAQ: ), so important. Apple is late to the market, as it often is, but it will likely be able to sell the HomePod as a . That should at least assure it a niche in the market, and . HomePod then becomes a means by which many other services are sold. Apple has the cash to make HomePod . Security is getting Apple , working alongside (NASDAQ: ), which knows that market. As to the iPhone 8 and X, which many analysts considered a bust when they were first announced, some of their best features, like power management, are . Phones don\u2019t just have the initial sell-through anymore. Apple has a huge business rehabbing and reselling phones, giving them a longer life in the market. What is happening right now is that the stock market is falling. Apple is not. The stock market is falling because interest rates are rising, and you can now get a safe return of 3-4% on your money, something that wasn\u2019t possible before. The economy is still growing at a good clip. Apple is growing faster than that, it\u2019s profitable, and while the go-go days are over, you can still make money in AAPL stock at these levels. Article printed from InvestorPlace Media, https://investorplace.com/2018/02/apple-inc-aapl-when-does-it-become-a-bargain/. \u00a92018 InvestorPlace Media, LLC  \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7   \u00b7    Financial Market Data powered by FinancialContent Services, Inc. All rights reserved. Nasdaq quotes delayed at least 15 minutes, all others at least 20 minutes. Copyright \u00a9 2018 InvestorPlace Media, LLC. All rights reserved. 9201 Corporate Blvd, Rockville, MD 20850.", "link": "https://investorplace.com/2018/02/apple-inc-aapl-when-does-it-become-a-bargain/", "source": "MarketWatch", "author": null, "tick": "AAPL", "headline": "When Does Apple Inc. Stock Become a Bargain? Now! | InvestorPlace"}
{"text": "Food  for thought for FinTech investors: emerging payment processing companies are  revolutionizing mobile payment technologies used in retail and restaurant  transactions. And  the sky\u2019s the limit for the mobile payment transaction world. According to  research data, the market is expected to reach a in the year 2020. Mobile  payments are undoubtedly changing the way the world shops and dines. The savviest investors are paying attention to  innovative technologies in vertical markets because digital wallets are  starting to replace physical wallets, as consumers are A digital wallet is an electronic device  that enables electronic transactions, including purchases made using a  smartphone. Clearly, smartphones are the new wallets. PayPal  (NASDAQ: ) doesn\u2019t use cryptocurrency, but Ceo  Dan Schulman called blockchain, the underlying technology,  a And Jack Dorsey, chairman and CEO of Square  Inc.(NYSE: ) and CEO of Twitter,  described blockchain as the . In  December 2017, Apple , introducing its own digital  wallet and simplifying  consumer purchasing using facial and fingerprint recognition technology.  Essentially- this marks a move towards cryptocurrency for Apple. BC-based  tech companies currently trying to break into the digital cryptocurrency space  include ( ; OTC: ), and ., both  of which are establishing themselves as players in the hospitality processing  industry. A  FinTech investor and start-up incubator already making moves in the  blockchain-enabled payment processing space is Victory Square Technologies,  Inc. . Victory  Square CEO Shafin Diamond Tejani has garnered a list of business accolades,  being named EY\u2019s Technology Entrepreneur of the Year 2015, Canadian Angel  Investor of the Year, BC Tech Person of the Year 2107, and BIV\u2019s Top Forty  Under 40. PayVida Solutions Inc. recently by Victory Square Technologies Inc. This Fintech investor and start-up  incubator has been making significant acquisitions with the addition of PayVida  to its portfolio of ventures. PayVida  is launching a global payment facilitator designed to disrupt traditional  banking and payment processing technologies for business owners, with plans to  incorporate digital \u2014 or cryptocurrencies into their own platform, and also with their  crypto wallets. \u201cPayVida provides solutions that challenge the tired and  uninspiring technologies that most banks and payment processing providers  offer,\u201d said Tejani, CEO, Victory Square. \u201cThey have established themselves by  offering less expensive pricing and same-day funding times that merchants have  never experienced with today\u2019s leading FinTech giants.\u201d PayVida  co-founder Robert Ronning said what is disruptive about PayVida\u2019s technology is  that it is a hybrid between merchant account providers and payment  facilitators. PayVida started in the restaurant business, working with industry  giant Glowbal Restaurant Group, led by Emad Yacoub. Ronning  said PayVida\u2019s platform and upcoming wallets will be a \u201cgame changer\u201d. \u201cWith our wallet, it will allow every merchant  to accept crypto, whether they are a PayVida merchant, or not. It will allow  them to get paid in their home currency (Canadian or US Dollars) whether the transaction  was processed in crypto or fiat. Our core developers are some of the strongest blockchain  developers available in the market,\u201d Ronning said. \u201cWhat\u2019s  great about our payment ecosystem is that it allows our technology to lend  itself to merchants, ISO\u2019s, ISV\u2019s, VARS, and wallets that are currently  available in marketplaces. It allows us to work with financial institutions,  which enables them to activate merchants in real-time with our smart terminal  and e-commerce solutions to make them quicker, more nimble, and offer more for  their consumer base. We will empower those potential partners, and our own  wallet, to have the most sophisticated means of payment.\u201d \u201cWe\u2019re  revolutionizing how payments are done, Ronning said. \u201cWe\u2019re the first in the  world that we know of that will give merchants   same-day funding and their employees with tip payouts access to a  prepaid credit card that we give our merchants.\u201d Moving  from a cash to a cryptocurrency society will enable merchants faster  transaction times and allow for quicker turnover. With cryptocurrency moving  from the margins to the mainstream and poised to replace cash - a cashless  society is seemingly just over the horizon. For most merchants, digitizing the  industry is looking very bright.  PayPal Holdings, Inc.  is an online payment processing company founded in 2002 by Elon Musk, Peter Thiel, Max Levchin, Ken Howery, Luke Nosek and Yu Pan. Based in  the U.S., PayPal operates a worldwide online  payments system that supports online money transfers and serves as an  electronic alternative to traditional paper methods like checks and money  orders.  Glance Technologies Inc. is a Vancouver-based financial technology  company. The Company focuses on developing mobile payment processing software  and smart phone applications. Glance Technologies serves customers in Canada,  the United States, and Europe.  Apple Pay is a mobile payment and digital wallet service  by Apple Inc. launched in October 2014. The service allows users to make  payments using an iPhone, Apple Watch, iPad or Mac. Apple  Pay does not require Apple Pay-specific terminals, and can work with existing  contactless terminals. Visa Inc. is an American multinational financial services  corporation. It facilitates throughout the world, most commonly through Visa-branded and . Visa does  not issue cards, extend credit or set rates and fees for consumers; rather,  Visa provides financial institutions with Visa-branded payment products that  they then use to offer credit, debit, prepaid and cash-access programs to their  customers. For a more in-depth look into (CSE:VST)  (OTC:VSQTF) (FWB:6F6) you can view the full report on . Nothing in this publication should be considered as personalized financial advice. We are not licensed under securities laws to address your particular financial situation. No communication by our employees to you should be deemed as personalized financial advice. Please consult a licensed financial advisor before making any investment decision. This is a paid advertisement and is neither an offer nor recommendation to buy or sell any security. We hold no investment licenses and are thus neither licensed nor qualified to provide investment advice. The content in this article is not provided to any individual with a view toward their individual circumstances. Baystreet.ca has been paid a fee of ten thousand dollars for Victory Square Technologies advertising and digital media. This compensation constitutes a conflict of interest as to our ability to remain objective in our communication regarding the profiled company. Because of this conflict, individuals are strongly encouraged to not use this newsletter as the basis for any investment decision. While all information is believed to be reliable, it is not guaranteed by us to be accurate. Individuals should assume that all information contained in our newsletter is not trustworthy unless verified by their own independent research. Also, because events and circumstances frequently do not occur as expected, there will likely be differences between any predictions and actual results. Always consult a licensed investment professional before making any investment decision. Be extremely careful, investing in securities carries a high degree of risk; you may likely lose some or all of the investment. Copyright 1998 - 2018 Media Corp. All rights reserved. Nasdaq Stocks: Information delayed 15 minutes. Non-Nasdaq Stocks: Information delayed 20 minutes. Bid and Ask quotation information for NYSE and AMEX securities is only available on a real time basis. Data is provided by QuoteMedia.com", "link": "http://www.baystreet.ca/articles/marketwatch.aspx?id=940", "source": "MarketWatch", "author": null, "tick": "AAPL", "headline": "\r\n\tBaystreet.ca - Will Cryptocurrency End Cash Transactions for Merchants?\r\n"}
{"text": "Founded in 1993 by brothers Tom and David Gardner, The Motley Fool helps millions of people attain financial freedom through our website, podcasts, books, newspaper column, radio show, and premium investing services. In any discussion of  these days, there's no escaping the subject of its legal troubles. The antitrust limelight shone on the company again last month after it was slapped with another fine, this one from the E.U.'s European Commission. Qualcomm's battles with regulators and customers are frustrating because they distract from the strides it's making in new growth opportunities including 5G, and the Internet of Things (IoT). Up-and-coming is already knee-deep in IoT, and as it demonstrated last quarter, it's working. With a market capitalization of just $631 million, Sierra may get overlooked by many investors. That's actually a good thing for a couple of reasons. Its IoT focus offers it limitless opportunities, as do Qualcomm's product diversification initiatives. So: Which is the better buy? Image source: Getty Images. Unfortunately for\u00a0Qualcomm shareholders, fiscal 2018's first quarter ended as the prior quarter did: With a massive fine, in this case, a $1.2 billion . Qualcomm intends to provide a \"financial guarantee\" as it battles the EU in court. Like other tech giants, Qualcomm's numbers took a temporary boost from the U.S. tax overhaul. Its conflicts with once again took a toll, but there were also several bright spots for Qualcomm. Excluding one-time items, total revenue of $6.04 billion was a 1% improvement year over year. As expected, earnings per share declined (thank you, Apple) 18% to $0.98 a share. Qualcomm's adjusted earnings are nothing to brag about, but there's a caveat. The highly profitable licensing unit's sales were just $1.3 billion last quarter, a 28% decline. However, as Qualcomm pointed out, a year ago, licensing revenue from Apple totaled $740 million. The iPhone maker has been withholding its royalty payments: If you add that figure back into the mix, Qualcomm's QTL division revenue would actually have risen 13% to $2.04 billion. First-quarter results were better than expected, but questions still loom. buyout bid for the company is still pending, as is Qualcomm's own long-standing offer for . There are also concerns about the slowing smartphone market in China, a nation whose sales are a key growth driver for the company. But, like its legal troubles, the China situation is likely a near-term hiccup, not a long-term problem. Image source: Getty Images. Growth investors in search of a pure-play IoT stock would be hard-pressed to find a better alternative than Sierra Wireless. The fact that its total revenue climbed 13% to $173.24 million last quarter was a feather in its cap. Better still was the way Sierra improved its top line -- with growth in each of its three divisions. Sales to original equipment manufacturers (OEM), Sierra's largest business, climbed 8.4% to $138.5 million, followed by a 39% jump in enterprise solution sales of $26.3 million. Sierra's IoT product offerings also include cloud and connectivity solutions. In the smallish, but fast-growing, cloud and IoT connectivity segment, revenue was $8.4 million, up 23% compared to a year ago. Due in part to increased product development spending, operating expenses rose 16% last quarter to $57.54 million. However, excluding a one-time charge of $2 million for Sierra's , and a $600,000 rise in amortization expenses, the increase in overhead would have been a more modest 11%. Sierra's gross margins improved an impressive 17% last quarter, more than offsetting its higher expenses. That, along with Sierra's revenue growth, boosted EPS to $0.04, a far better result than the loss of $0.06 a share a year ago. For bargain hunters, Sierra is valued well below its peers by virtually all metrics, including share price that's a meager 16.7 times forward earnings. A year from now, Qualcomm shareholders will likely look back in relief that its worst days are over. Until then, the company continues to expand its product portfolio to take advantage of the limitless opportunities IoT, 5G, and similar markets represent. Oh, and let's not forget that while they wait, shareholders will enjoy a dividend that currently yields 3.35%. The relatively small size that leads many investors to miss Sierra may be one reason its stock is such a value, but it's a positive for another reason. Given the massiveness of the IoT market already -- let alone where it's headed -- Sierra won't need to dominate connectivity, OEM, or enterprise segments to dramatically move its revenue needle. Because of those things, as well as its recent performance and slow-but-steady revenue diversification, Sierra Wireless gets the nod as the better stock. Tim has been writing professionally for several years after spending 18 years (Whew! Was it that long?)in both the retail and institutional side of the financial services industry. Tim resides in Portland, Oregon with his three children and the family dog.", "link": "https://www.fool.com/investing/2018/02/09/better-buy-sierra-wireless-inc-vs-qualcomm.aspx?source=djc&utm_campaign=article&utm_medium=feed&utm_source=djc", "source": "MarketWatch", "author": "Tim Brugger", "tick": "AAPL", "headline": "\n            \n    Better Stock: Sierra Wireless Inc. vs. Qualcomm -- The Motley Fool\n\n        "}
